Data Warehousing and Business Intelligence

Course Overview:
This course provides a comprehensive exploration of data warehousing and business intelligence concepts. You will learn about the purpose and benefits of data warehousing, the Extract, Transform, Load (ETL) process, dimensional modeling, and techniques for business intelligence analysis. By the end of the course, you will understand how to design and implement a data warehouse, perform ETL operations, and leverage business intelligence tools for data analysis and reporting.

Course Duration:
The course is designed to be completed in approximately 10 weeks, assuming a pace of 4-6 hours of study per week.

Course Objectives:

Understand the fundamentals of data warehousing and its role in modern data management.
Learn the Extract, Transform, Load (ETL) process for integrating data into a data warehouse.
Gain proficiency in dimensional modeling techniques for designing efficient data warehouses.
Explore business intelligence concepts and tools for data analysis and reporting.
Develop practical skills to implement and manage data warehousing and business intelligence solutions.
Course Outline:

Week 1: Introduction to Data Warehousing
Understanding the concept and benefits of data warehousing.
Overview of data warehousing architectures.
Exploring the roles and responsibilities of data warehouse professionals.
Introduction to key components: data sources, ETL processes, data marts, and reporting.

Week 2: ETL Processes
Understanding the Extract, Transform, Load (ETL) process.
Exploring data extraction techniques from various sources.
Techniques for data transformation and cleansing.
Best practices for data loading into the data warehouse.

Week 3: Dimensional Modeling
Introduction to dimensional modeling concepts.
Understanding dimensions, hierarchies, and fact tables.
Techniques for designing star and snowflake schemas.
Implementing slowly changing dimensions.

Week 4: Data Warehouse Implementation
Planning and designing a data warehouse architecture.
Identifying and modeling business requirements.
Translating business requirements into a dimensional model.
Physical implementation considerations.

Week 5: Data Warehouse Management
Data quality management in data warehousing.
Data governance and metadata management.
Performance optimization techniques for data warehouses.
Managing data refresh and incremental updates.

Week 6: Business Intelligence Concepts
Understanding the role and importance of business intelligence.
Exploring different types of business intelligence tools and technologies.
Introduction to data visualization and reporting.
Overview of OLAP (Online Analytical Processing) and data mining.

Week 7: Business Intelligence Tools
Introduction to popular business intelligence tools (e.g., Tableau, Power BI).
Hands-on experience with data visualization and report creation.
Designing interactive dashboards for data analysis.
Exploring advanced features of business intelligence tools.

Week 8: Advanced Business Intelligence Techniques
Introduction to advanced analytics techniques (e.g., predictive analytics, text analytics).
Applying data mining algorithms for business intelligence.
Leveraging machine learning for data-driven insights.
Real-time analytics and streaming data processing.

Week 9: Business Intelligence Deployment and Integration
Strategies for deploying business intelligence solutions.
Integration of business intelligence with operational systems.
Data security and access control in business intelligence environments.
Performance monitoring and optimization in business intelligence.

Week 10: Course Project and Final Assessment
Applying the knowledge gained throughout the course to a real-world project.
Designing and implementing a data warehouse and business intelligence solution.
Creating reports and dashboards for data analysis and decision-making.
Final assessment to test your understanding of the course material.
Course Resources:

Textbook: "The Data Warehouse Toolkit: The Definitive Guide to Dimensional Modeling" by Ralph Kimball and Margy Ross.
Online resources and tutorials on data warehousing, ETL processes, and business intelligence.
Business intelligence tools (e.g., Tableau Public, Power BI Desktop) for hands-on practice.
Sample datasets and exercises to reinforce learning.
Upon completing this course, you will have a strong foundation in data warehousing and business intelligence, equipping you with the skills to design, implement, and leverage data warehouses for effective data analysis and decision-making in various domains.




